text.tspan: Teaching Phylogenetics and Evolution through interactive
Python coding exercises
toytree
Tree visualization, manipulation, and analysis library
core: Toytree object for data manipulation and visualization
io: tree parsing, i/o, data and meta-data
distance: tree and node distance functions
enumerate: generators over edges, quartets, bipartitions, etc.
mod: tree manipulations (root, ladderize, PL, SPR, ...)
rtree: random tree generation (birth-death,
infer: didactic functions and lessons for tree inference
pcm: phylogenetic comparative methods (sim or fit models)
ipcoal
Coalescent simulations and analysis of multispecies data
core: Model object for parameterizing msprime simulations
sim: simulate linked or unlinked trees and sequences
phylo: wrappers to infer gene trees from simulated sequence data
msc: multispecies coalescent likelihood and related functions
smc: sequentially markov coalescent likelihood and related functions
draw: toytree-based plotting functions for species and gene trees
Learning to interpret phylogenetic trees and patterns of
evolution on trees is fundamental to a training in biology.
Interactive coding exercises that allow students to modify and
visualize trees can provide a framework to understand phylogeny
as both a statistical data structure and evolutionary model.
The toytree Python library can be used to generate research
quality figures, to perform evolutionary analyses, and for teaching
phylogenetics and evolution through built-in didactic exercises.
The coalescent is a mathematical model for the distribution of
genealogies among a set of samples in a population. It forms the
basis of modern statistical methods in popgen and phylogenetics.
However, it remains a challenging subject for beginning students.
The ipcoal Python library provides an easy to use wrapper around
msprime to setup and perform coalescent simulations, to visualize
results with toytree, and to explore trees and sequences in the
context of phylogenetic models and inference tools.
Development of toytree and ipcoal is supported by grant
NSF-DEB 20146813 awarded to D.E.
Deren Eaton, Columbia University
